If we view   on odd plaquettes as the flux in  gauge theory, we
find that the low energy sector of model is identical to a  lattice gauge
theory, at least for infinite systems. This suggests that the low energy
effective theory of our model is a  lattice gauge theory.

However, one may object this result by pointing out that the low energy sector
of our model is also identical to an Ising model with one spin on each the odd
plaquette. Thus the the low energy effective theory should be the Ising model.
We would like to point out that although the low energy sector of our model is
identical to an Ising model for infinite systems, the low energy sector of our
model is different from an Ising model for finite systems.  For example, on a
finite even by even lattice with periodic boundary condition, the ground state
of our model has a four-fold degeneracy. The Ising model
does not have such a degeneracy.  Also, our model contains an excitation that
can be identified as  charge (see below). Therefore, the low energy
effective theory of our model is a  lattice gauge theory instead of an
Ising model.  The  excitations on odd plaquettes can be viewed as
the  vortex excitations in the  lattice gauge theory.

 


 

A hopping of the  charge around four nearest neighbor even plaquettes.
 

Three types of strings and emerging fermions 

What is the  charge excitations?  We note that, in the closed-string
condensed state, the action of the closed-string operator stringOP  on the
ground state is trivial.  This suggests that the action of the open-string
operators on the ground state only depend on the ends of strings, since two
open strings with the same ends only differ by a closed-string.  Therefore, an
open-string operator create two particles at its ends when acting on the
string condensed state.  Since the strings in stringOP  only connect even
plaquettes, the particle corresponding to the ends of the open strings always
live on the even plaquettes. We will call such a string T1 string.  Form the
commutation relation between  and the open-string operators, we
find that the open-string operators flip the sign of  at its
ends.  Thus each particle created by the open-string operators has an energy
.  Now, let us consider the hopping of one such particle around four
nearest neighbor even plaquettes (see Fig.  ). We see that the
product of the the four hopping amplitudes is given by the eigenvalue of 
 on the odd plaquette in the middle of the four even
plaquettes. This is exactly the relation between charge and
flux.  Thus if we identify  on odd plaquettes as  flux,
then the ends of strings on even plaquettes will correspond to the 
charges.  We note that, due to the closed-string condensation, the ends of
open strings are not confined and have only short ranged interactions between
them.  Thus the  charges behave like quasiparticles with no string
attached.

Just like the  charges, a pair  vortices is also created by an open
string operator.  Since the  vortices correspond to flipped 
 on odd  plaquettes, the open-string operator that create 
vortices is also given by stringOP , except now the product is over a
string that connect odd  plaquettes.  We will call such a string T2
string. (The strings connecting even  plaquettes were called T1
strings.)

We would like to point out that the reference state (the no string state)
for the T2 string is different from that of the T1 string.  
The no-T2-string is given
by  with spin pointing in -direction on even sites and
-direction on odd sites. Since the T1 and T2 strings have different
reference state, we cannot have a dilute gas of the T1 strings and the T2
strings at the same time.  One can easily check that the T2 string operators
also commute with . Therefore, the ground state , in
addition to the T1 closed-string condensation, also has a T2 closed-string
condensation.  

The hopping of a  vortex is induced by a short T2 open-string.  Since the
T2 open-strings operators all commute with each other, the  vortex behave
like bosons.  Similarly, the  charges also behave like bosons. However,
T1 open-string operators and T2 open-string operators do not commute.  As a
result, the ends of T1 string and the ends of T2 string have nontrivial mutual
statistics.  As we have already shown that moving a  charge around a
 vortex generate a phase , the  charges  and the  vortices
have a semionic mutual statistics.

The T3 strings are defined as bound states of T1 and T2 strings.  The ground
state also has a condensation of T3 closed-strings. The ends of T3 string, as
bound states of the  charges  and the  vortices, are
fermions . We note that the ends of T3 strings, and hence the fermions,
live on the links. It is interesting to see that string condensation in our
model directly leads to  gauge structure and three new type of
quasiparticles:  charge,  vortex, and fermions. Fermions, as ends of
open T3 strings, emerge from our purely bosonic model.

Since ends of T1 string are  charges, the T1 string can be viewed as
strings of  "electric" flux. Similarly, the T2 string can be viewed as
strings of  "magnetic" flux.

Classification of different string condensations by PSG 

