PSG and ends of condensed strings 

From the different  and , we see that the above
four phases have different string condensations. However, they all have the
same symmetry.  This raises an issue. Without symmetry breaking, how do we
know the above four phases are really different phases? How do we know that it
is impossible to change one string condensed state to another without a phase
transition?

In the following, we will show that the different string condensations can be
described by different PSG's (just like different symmetry breaking orders can
be described by different symmetry groups of ground states.) In
Wqoslpub,Wqogen , different quantum orders were introduced via their
different PSG's. The connection between string condensation and PSG allows us
to connect string condensation to the quantum order introduced in
Wqoslpub,Wqogen .  In particular, the PSG's are shown to be a universal
property of a quantum phase, which can be changed only by phase transitions.
Thus the different PSG's for the different string condensed states indicate
that those different string condensed states belong to different quantum
phases.

When closed-strings condense, the ends of open strings behave like independent
particles. Let us consider two particles states  described by
the two ends of a T1 string. Note that the ends of the T1 strings, and hence
the  charges, only live on the even plaquettes. Here  and 
 label the even plaquettes. For our model ,  is
an energy eigenstate and the  charges do not hop. Here we would like to
add a term 
 
to the Hamiltonian. The -term 
makes the  charges to hop among the even plaquettes with a hopping
amplitude of order . The dynamics of the two  charges is described by
the following effective Hamiltonian in the two-particle Hilbert space
 
where  describes the hopping of the first particle  and
 describes the hopping of the second particle .  Now we can
define the PSG in a string condensed state. The PSG is nothing but the
symmetry group of the hopping Hamiltonian .

Due to the translation symmetry of the underlying model , we
may naively expect the hopping Hamiltonian of the  charge  also 
have a translation symmetry
 
The above implies PSG = translation symmetry group.  It turns out that
HTxy  is too strong. The underlying spin model can have translation
symmetry even when  does not satisfy HTxy .  However, the
possible symmetry groups of  (the PSG's) are strongly constrained by
the translation symmetry of the underlying spin model. In the follow, we will
explain why the PSG can be different from the symmetry group of the physical
spin model, and what conditions that the PSG must satisfy in order to be
consistent with the translation symmetry of the spin model.

We note that a string
always has two ends. Thus a physical state always has an even number of 
charges. The actions of translation on a two-particle state are given by
 
The phases  and 
