In Wqoexct , the spin-1/2 model HV  (with ) was viewed as a
hardcore boson model. The model was solved using slave-boson approach by
splitting a boson into two fermions. Then it was shown the fermion hopping
Hamiltonian for  and  states have different symmetries, or invariant
under different PSG's. According to the arguments in Wqoslpub , the
different PSG's imply different quantum orders in the  and  ground
state states.  The PSG's obtained in Wqoexct  for the  and 
phases agrees exactly with the fermion PSG's that we obtained above.  This
example shows that the PSG's introduced in Wqoexct,Wqogen  
are the symmetry groups of the hopping Hamiltonian of the ends of condensed
strings. The PSG description and the string-condensation description of
quantum orders are intimately related.

Here we would like to point out that the PSG's introduced in
Wqoslpub,Wqogen  are all fermion PSG's. They are only one of many
different kinds of PSG's that can be used to characterize quantum orders.  In
general, a quantum ordered state may contain condensations of several types of
strings. The ends of each type of condensed strings will have their own PSG.

Massless fermion and PSG in string condensed state 

In Wqoslpub,WZqoind , it was pointed out that PSG can protect
masslessness of the emerging fermions, just like symmetry can protect the
masslessness of Nambu-Goldstone bosons.  In this section, we are going to
study an exact soluble spin- model with string
condensation and emerging massless fermions.  Through this soluble model, we
demonstrate how PSG that characterizes the string condensation can protect
the masslessness of the fermions.  The exact soluble model that we are going
to study is motivated by Kitaev's exact soluble spin-1/2 model on honeycomb
lattice.


