bosons do not exactly condense but the boson operator has an
algebraic-long-range correlation.


Emerging chiral symmetry from PSG 

psiU1c  describes the low energy dynamics of the ends of open strings (the
fermion ) and the "condensed" closed strings (the  gauge field).
The fermions and gauge boson are massless and interact with each other. Here
we would like to address an important question: after integrating out high
energy fermions and gauge fluctuations, do fermions and gauge boson remain to
be massless? In general, interaction between massless excitations will
generate a mass term for them, unless the masslessness is protected by
symmetry or some other things.  We know that due to the  gauge
invariance, the radiative corrections cannot generate counter term that break
the  gauge invariance. Thus radiative corrections cannot generate mass
for the  gauge boson.  For the fermions, if the theory has a chiral
symmetry , 
, then the radiative corrections cannot generate counter
terms that break the chiral symmetry and thus cannot generate mass for fermions.
Although the low energy effective theory psiU1c  appears to have the chiral
symmetry, in fact it does not. This is because that
psiU1c  is derived from a lattice model. It contains many other higher
order terms summarized by the  in psiU1c . Those higher order terms
do not have the chiral symmetry. To see this, we note that the action of
 on  is realized by a 4 by 4 matrix 
. We also note that the periodic
boundary conditions of  in the reduced Brillouin zone are given
by
 
We find that the action of  is incompatible with the periodic boundary
conditions since  does not commute with  and
. Therefore the chiral symmetry generated by 
cannot be realized on lattice.  Due to the lack of chiral symmetry, it appears
that the radiative corrections can generate a mass term
 
which is allowed by the symmetry.

The lack of chiral symmetry on lattice makes it very difficult to study
massless fermions/quarks in lattice gauge theory. In last a few years, this
problem was solved using the Ginsparg-Wilson
relation. In the following, we would like to
show that there is another way to solve the massless-fermion/chiral-symmetry
problem. We will show that our model has an emerging chiral symmetry that
appear only at low energies. The low energy chiral symmetry comes from the
non-trivial quantum order and the associated PSG in the string condensed
ground state.  
The Dirac operator in our model satisfies a linear relation
 
in contrast to the non-linear Ginsparg-Wilson relation
 
Because of the low energy chiral symmetry, all the  families
of Dirac fermions remain massless even after we include the radiative
corrections from the interaction with the  gauge bosons.


